he public about what to eat or not. These conversations about “social change as eating” reflect American ideals of freedom, purity, and virtue. Drawing on social and political history as well as the history of science and popular culture, Dangerous Digestion examines how American ideas about dietary reform mirror broader thinking about social reform. Inspired by new scientific studies of the human body as a metabiome—a collaboration of species rather than an isolated, intact, protected, and bounded individual—E. Melanie DuPuis invokes a new metaphor—digestion—to reimagine the American body politic, opening social transformations to ideas of mixing, fermentation, and collaboration. In doing so, the author explores how social activists can rethink politics as inclusive processes that involve the inherently risky mixing of cultures, standpoints, and ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDietxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aDietxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aFood habitszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aamerican body politic.  aamerican dietary guidelines.  aamerican eating.  adangerous diets.  adietary control in america.  adietary reform.  adigestion.  afood and nutrition.  afood control.  afood habits in the us.  afood obsession.  afood science.  agut health.  ahistory of food.  ahistory of nutrition.  aideal diet for humans.  aingestion.  amarketing nutrition.  apopular diets.  asocial activism in america.  asocial aspects of food.  awhat should i eat.  awhite middle class diets.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027547840uhttps://doi.org/10.